<div style="max-width: 1200px; margin: auto;">
<h3>The position</h3>
OurWorldInData.org is a web publication that presents academic research on how living conditions change around the world. To expand the visualization tools and website that allow us to present this research online we are looking for a new OurWorldInData Web Developer.

The web developer will work on the data visualization tools at the University of Oxford for a fixed term (flexible arrangements â€“ see below; and there is the possibility for extension). It is a position at a world class academic institution with the unique opportunity to contribute to a data visualization publication that makes research openly and freely available. The project is highly visible, you will work on a project that will remain in use for a long time, and you contribute to the development of tools that are open source. You will be working very closely with researchers at the University of Oxford and with academics around the world.

The new web developer will work with the small OurWorldInData team and will have substantial influence on the process. The web developer is therefore expected to take a leading role in continuing the work on the OurWorldInData-Grapher (details on this tool follow below).

The successful candidate must have very good knowledge of JavaScript â€“ in particular D3.js and MVC frameworks, ideally Backbone.js. Knowledge of HTML, CSS, WordPress, and PHP are also essential. Additional knowledge of Laravel, NVD3, datamaps, and the OurWorldInData-Grapher are a plus.

We are looking for candidates as soon as possible to work on this project. The 2016 OurWorldInData Web Developer position was made possible by a crowdfunding campaign in November 2015 which was initiated by readers of OurWorldInData and which was backed by 139 generous supporters (<a href="https://www.tilt.com/tilts/help-save-ourworldindataorg?lightbox=tilt-joined">here is the full list</a>) â€“ among many others that made this new position possible were James Beshara, Marc Andreessen, Paul Graham, Ramez Naam, and Steven Berlin Johnson.

The web developer will be employed for a fixed-term (to be negotiated with the successful applicant/s). Applications are welcomed from students at Oxford; and at the same time we are open to requests for remote and flexible working from web developers around the world.
<h3>Our World In Data</h3>
OurWorldInData is an online publication that shows how living conditions around the world are changing. It is published at the University of Oxford and covers a wide range of topics across many academic disciplines: Trends in health, food provision, the growth and distribution of incomes, violence, rights, wars, culture, energy use, education, and environmental changes are empirically analyzed and visualized in this web publication. For each topic the quality of the data is discussed and, by pointing the visitor to the sources, this website is also a database of databases.
Covering all of these aspects in one resource makes it possible to understand how the observed long-run trends are interlinked and the research on the causal relations is presented to the audience of interested readers, journalists, academics, and policy people.
But have a look at it yourself to see what it is about:
<ul>
	<li>1st Example: <a href="http://ourworldindata.org/data/population-growth-vital-statistics/life-expectancy/">The data-entry on life expectancy</a> is showing the development of child mortality over the long run. It is one of dozens of similar data-entries on a wide range of topics.</li>
	<li>2nd Example: <a href="http://ourworldindata.org/VisualHistoryOf/Violence.html">â€˜The most peaceful time in our species existenceâ€™</a>. This is one of five presentations that present the content from several data-entries and give a comprehensive picture on how our world is changing.</li>
</ul>
We want to bring the empirical research to the greatest possible audience so that we understand our world and make informed decisions for the future of our world.

Our role model in making knowledge available and in creating and reviewing content is the <a href="http://plato.stanford.edu/">Stanford Encyclopaedia of Philosophy</a>. To make research publicly known is a democratic project and OurWorldInData is a public good: The publication is freely available online, all data is available for download, the visualizations are available under a permissive Creative Commons license, and all tools to publish OurWorldInData are open source.

The project is based at the University of Oxfordâ€™s <a href="http://inet.ox.ac.uk">Institute for New Economic Thinking</a> at the Oxford Martin School. The Oxford Martin School is an interdisciplinary institution within the University and for this publication we work together with the network of academic and the very helpful administrative team of the institution. The research programme dedicated to this publication is directed by Dr Max Roser who started to work on this publication more than 5 years ago and leads the technical and content development of the project. The long experience with this project gives us a clear idea for the future of this publication.

The long-term plan is to establish OurWorldInData as an open-access web publication, written for anyone interested in global development, and co-written with experts, that uses accessible data visualizations to present empirical research on living conditions around the world, how they are changing and why.
<h3>Main Responsibilities of the Web Developer</h3>
<ul>
	<li>Extend the functionality of the data base that stores the visualised data.
<ul>
	<li>Among other aspects a version control for the stored data and data handling capabilities have to be added.</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>Support the development of the interactive visualisations.
<ul>
	<li>Design of the layout and technical framework for the different types of visualizations used on OurWorldInData.</li>
	<li>Build re-usable templates for each type of visualization: slope graphs, scatter plots, &amp; (world) maps.</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>Working in team with Max Roser and the first web developer.</li>
	<li>Improve the usability of the online publication OurWorldInData.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Skills &amp; Requirements</h3>
<ul>
	<li>Very interested and experienced with online data visualization â€“ especially with the visualization of time-series and panel data.</li>
	<li>Very good knowledge of Javascript and D3.js and Backbone.js, or another MVC framework.
<ul>
	<li>Knowledge of <a href="http://nvd3.org/">NVD3.js,</a> and <a href="http://datamaps.github.io/">datamaps</a> is an advantage.</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>Knowledge of HTML, CSS, PHP, WordPress and ideally Laravel.</li>
	<li>Ability to work independently and as part of a team. Pragmatic and organized.</li>
	<li>Design experience.</li>
	<li>Enthusiasm for development economics, economic &amp; social history, and communication of research.</li>
	<li>Experience with Adobe Illustrator and print publishing is an advantage.</li>
	<li>We like to see evidence of your work, either open-source or from code you can send us over for review.</li>
</ul>
<p dir="ltr"><strong dir="ltr"><strong>Location</strong> and employment:</strong> We are looking for a candidate as soon as possible after 25 January 2016.</p>
<p dir="ltr">We are open to requests for remote and flexible working from web developers around the world.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Not only remote work is possible, we can also offer you an office at the University of Oxford where you will be based in Eagle House in Jericho (Oxford, UK) â€“ a really nice part of the town.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Students at the University of Oxford are welcomed to apply and it is possible to find a flexible solution that will be compatible with your working hours and workload for your studies.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The successful candidate is expected to start working early in 2016. We will have work for several months but suitable candidates that would be available for shorter contract length (such as students) should also get in contact.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The reviewing of applications will begin on 24 January, and will continue until the position is filled.</p>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>Renumeration</strong>: Â£121.43 per day [Â£16.19 per hour; 7.5 hours per day].</p>

<h3>Impact of the project</h3>
In June 2014 Max Roser made the website available online. Since then more than 1,500,000 people have visited OurWorldInData.org.
And more than 180 articles portrayed the project or used material on global development from OurWorldInData. All are listed at: <a href="http://www.ourworldindata.org/media-coverage">www.ourworldindata.org/media-coverage</a>. English-language media outlets covering and using OurWorldInData include The New York Times, The Washington Post, Forbes, Slate, Vox, The Guardian, The Financial Times, and the BBC.
The content is also popular on social media. From the feedback we receive we also know that the content of OurWorldInData is used widely in teaching and lectures.
<h3>The data visualisations and the publication platform of OurWorldInData</h3>
The heart of the web publication is the <em>OurWorldInData-Grapher</em>. Zdenek Hynek â€“ the first OurWorldInData Web Developer â€“ developed this tool with Max Roser in 2015.

The Grapher is is a combination of 2 tools:
<ol style="list-style-type: upper-roman;">
	<li>A first tool allows the author to upload data into one central SQL database â€“ as opposed to the inferior system in which data is stored in individual unconnected .csv files. In the process of uploading the data, the author can store all the relevant information about the data source so that the authors get credited and the definitions, units, and other relevant information get stored with the data.</li>
	<li>A second tool then allows to pull any of the data from this database and visualize it in an interactive chart in many, many different ways.</li>
</ol>
The backend is written in PHP using the <a href="http://laravel.com/">Laravel Framework</a>. The frontend is written using <a href="http://backbonejs.org/">Backbone.js</a>, <a href="http://nvd3.org/">NVD3.js,</a> and <a href="http://datamaps.github.io/">datamaps</a>.
<ul>
	<li>You find more information on the OurWorldInData-Grapher and the source code on GitHub: <a href="https://github.com/OurWorldInData/our-world-in-data-grapher">https://github.com/OurWorldInData/our-world-in-data-grapher</a></li>
	<li>Additional information can be found here on OurWorldInData: <a href="http://ourworldindata.org/owid-grapher/">ourworldindata.org/owid-grapher</a></li>
</ul>
<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2"></a>OurWorldInData.org is published on WordPress and experience with this CMS is very helpful.

<strong>Please get in contact with Max Roser â€“ %CODE1% â€“ if you are interested in this job. Please provide a CV, refer to your previous work that is relevant for this position, and explain why you are interested in this project and why you would be suited to carry out the task. It would of course be helpful if you could look at the OurWorldInData-Grapher and OurWorldInData.org and make suggestions of what you would like to improve and how.
</strong>

Very much looking forward! Good luck!

&nbsp;

